english:
  title: The Swallow
  author: Baek Won-hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Year after year you come from distant lands,
    where clouds and waters blur the southern reaches.
    Seeking shelter, you cling to the deepest trees when rain falls,
    and gather mud, pecking at blossoms as they drift down.

    Your chirping breaks the silence of the spring pavilion,
    your feet dimple the still pond on fair-weather days.
    Your urgent cries seem to ask, "Where is the master?"
    yet my solitary eyes see clearly—
    you seek my quiet refuge as your own.
  footnotes:
    - The swallow serves as a symbol of transience and seasonal return in classical East Asian poetry, embodying both the cyclical nature of time and the yearning for home.
